===Etymology===
On March 4, 1681, Charles II of England granted a land tract to William Penn for the area that now includes Pennsylvania. Penn then founded a colony there as a place of religious freedom for Quakers, and named it for the {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|sylva}}, {{m|la|silva}} meaning "wood", thus "Pennsylvania."

